reviews.review_text: Great recording Suffice to say, I prefer auds to sbd's, and this is one hell of an aud. Thanks folks.

I didn't know Bob Menke well, yet I had met him later on at the S.F. Civic, indeed he name was well know for his great reputation for recording, I also recorded this show myself but ...! Even though it was probably the best sound they ever had at U.C.L.A. and consequently my best recording, especially since as it was noted elsewhere about Bob Menke's recording, I too got that excellent instrument separation effect (for lack of a better term to describe i.e. I don't really like calling it an effect as if it where something artificial via some post-processing; no it was definitely real) And quite noticable, so it was pretty surprising for a "binoral" recording, I remember wondering about well, in disgussing this show with others! Someone, seemed to think that some parts of, or somehow they had used ideas from, or were returning to the '73-'74 so-called "Wall of Sound" approach or? I was standing roughly where Mark Severson was (who I knew much better than Bob Menke) and using Audio Technica 811 mics into a JVC KD2 deck with Super-ANRS noise reduction which was similar to Dolby C; which I purchased 13 months earlier i.e. before both the Sony D5 was released and long before Dolby C was available on a portable. 
     Nevertheless, since a soundboard came out I eventually taped over it with the board!
     I too liked the "Stella Blue", but I liked others versions better for example, the one I recorded at Winterland '78, (mine doesn't cut like the board), Denver McNichol's, (since it rained at Red Rocks), this year or San Francisco Orpheum '76.
     I vote this as one of the best "Shakedown Street"->"Bertha" with the revolving accent on a chosen beat! The whole show is fairly good just like the San Diego shows before it.

     Augy
     San Diego

This show smoked right out of the gate and didn't let up...very sweet start to finish. You could really hear Deal being converted from the straight ahead song to what would later become a full-out jam...this sounded like mid-transition and showed what potential it had as a set closer. The whole show was so solid I remembered why '79 was such a great year. There weren't a lot of omg moments but the boys just rocked all night...exactly what I hoped for every time I walked into a venue to catch them...enjoy!
30 years ago today! Check out the very subtle Mind Left Body tease going into Stella Blue.  It's perfect, and should have been there every time they played that tune.
Jack Straw Blast Off! My oh my, here is Lesh as the main thrusters on a trip to Mars... a Jack Straw for the ages!
